space: Greetings! neighborhood_overview: My neighborhood in Midtown East is called Murray Hill. The area is very centrally located with easy access to explore . The apartment is about 5 blocks (7 minute walk) to the United Nations and Grand Central Station the main and most historic train station.  Grand Central will give you access to every train in the city. The apartment is also very close to main attractions, It's about a 10 minute walk to both the Empire State Building and Times Square.  There's a great shopping area with dozens of stores including H&M, Zara, The Gap, BeBe and the world famous Macy's department store. These shops are a 10 minute walk up East 34th Street from 5th avenue and 8th avenue.   If you would like to stay local in the area, there is a very long & famous strip of bars and restaurants along 3rd avenue, which is just around the corner from the apartment. It's commonly known as the 3rd avenue strip.
notes: Read My Full Listing For All Information. New York City really is the city that doesn't sleep. There's a constant flow of people, bikes and cars. The city can be noisy at times, if you're a light sleeper, ear plugs would help. Check out my local guide book for things to do.
transit: From the apartment is a 10 minute walk to Grand Central Station on East 42nd Street, a 10 minute walk to the Empire State Building on East 34th Street and 5th Avenue, a 10 minute walk to Times Square on West 42 Street and about 20 minutes walk to Central Park on 59th Street. Depending on how long you are staying, I would recommend a 7 day unlimited metro card. This allows you to travel unlimited all day and night on any train or bus in and outside of the city.  Grand Central Station is the main NYC train station. You can find any train connection and get anywhere in Manhattan from Grand Central Station. You can get to Brooklyn, Queens, The Bronx and Staten Island from Grand Central Station The M15 bus is around the corner on 2nd avenue. This bus will take you from uptown Harlem to the East Village and South Street Seaport. name: Cozy Clean Guest Room - Family Apt
summary: Our best guests are seeking a safe, clean, spare room in a family apartment.  They are comfortable being independent, accommodating of family noise (quiet hours 11pm-7am), and aren't afraid of a friendly two year old golden lab (dog).  Our guests aren't put off by an old bathroom that while perfectly clean, has some peeling paint.  In short, our guests want to feel like they are staying at their sister's apartment while visiting the city! (only their sister changed the sheets and cleaned).
space: Stay in my family's little  guest room and enjoy privacy, a warm welcome, and security.  Your guest room is comfortable and clean.   It is small but well outfitted, has a single bed and a fabulous mattress which is firm and yet pillowy on top, all at the same time. The bathroom is shared and immediately across the hall. ("Shared" in the sense it isn't "en suite." The family will use our second bath while you are staying with us). The bathroom is fully supplied with shampoo, conditioner, scrub, soap, towels. There is a window air conditioner in summer, ceiling fan, abundant pre-war construction apartment heat.  No smoking. I leave out a simple self serve breakfast: granola, yogurt, fruit.  We may chat with you over coffee, or perhaps you'll hit us on a busy day when we are already out and have left the coffee for you to serve yourself. Coffee or tea are available anytime. notes: Because we are an active family, I guarantee this is not a suitable room if you are seeking a quiet retreat to write the great American novel or work on business from your room.  Our best guests are out and about.
transit: The number 1 train stops at 110th Street/Cathedral Parkway, just two blocks from our apartment.
access: Guests will be able to come and go as they need and will enjoy complete privacy in their bedroom.  Guests will serve themselves breakfast from the kitchen, and enjoy eating in the lovely pre-war dining room.
interaction: My modern family is super busy with lots of coming and going.  You may encounter someone at home doing homework in the living room or me making dinner in the kitchen. I will always be available by text.
house_rules: No smoking. In fact, there is no smoking anywhere in the building or in front of the building.   Return home by midnight.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Welcome to family life with my oldest two away at college all the way down to a seventh grader. You may see everything from lively dinner conversation to a nearly empty apartment with everyone out enjoying the city.  I'm friendly, leave tea and coffee always available and responsive to a guest's needs.  My family has enjoyed everything from the guest who tends towards the private as well as the ones who dive in with the science experiment! 
Hosting through Airbnb has created a wonderful opportunity to meet people from all over the world, plot their addresses, and  learn about other places.   I began hosting through Airbnb four years ago as a work-from-home job. I continue because the whole family entirely grooves on the notion we get to meet people from all over the world and help them visit our city.

name: Cute & Cozy Lower East Side 1 bdrm
summary: Live like a New Yorker instead of a stuffy, tiny, overpriced hotel. My small yet cozy one bedroom apartment is nestled in the southern part of the historic lower east side, steps to the subway and walking distance to the coolest neighborhoods.
space: PLEASE NOTE: do not automatically book with out messaging me first. Thanks! My apartment is a cute, cozy, 1 bdrm apt in the Lower East Side (LES) adjacent to Chinatown in lower Manhattan, steps to F train, East Broadway stop and very close to Canal/Delancey streets where many hip bars, restaurants and shops are in the LES. Apt is clean, has a fully equipped kitchen, cable TV, A/C, heat, and wireless internet. Apt is located on 2nd floor of well maintained walk up building. Walking distance to Soho, East Village, Little Italy, Chinatown and very close to Dumbo and Williamsburg, Brooklyn. You have place to yourself-better than a hotel!  Prices listed are for up to two people only. Possible to accommodate a 3rd (for extra charge), but ideal for two.   Nighty rate: $125 - $150 a night for up to two people depending on time of year. $10 extra per person after 2 people.  As of now, I prefer booking for minimum 7 days and more. Might make an exception to fill in time slots, so inquire anyway.

neighborhood_overview: Historically, the Lower East Side was a stopping ground for immigrants who just arrived in NYC and was filled with tenements. There is an awesome Tenement Museum now on Orchard street, not far from my apartment. The Lower East Side has, in my opinion, two identities. The eastern side is very residential. The western, more in part is a hip, night time destinations with many bars, restaurants, galleries, cafes, independent shops, etc. My apartment is a couple of minutes from the hip part.  My particular street is very much in transition definitely going through gentrification. My block has now three renovated buildings, including mine and I suspect in a few years, will be completely different.  My immediate neighborhood is a mix of people - a real reflection of NYC diversity - Asian, Latin, Jewish, Black, young professionals, hipsters, artists, etc. It's a cool mix. The street is urban for sure but very safe. My building is filled with young professionals, creative types - one married co
notes: This is my personal apartment. It's not a business. It's not a hotel. It's not perfect. I host often and keep up with my place because of that. I try to keep it as clean as possible. However, it does have imperfections like anyone's home. If you expect perfection, it's best you book a hotel. :)
transit: F train, East Broadway stop is seconds away, very convenient and per my reviews, one of the things people love about my place.  The East Broadway stop is the last stop in Manhattan before it heads to Dumbo in Brooklyn The F train also goes up the center of Manhattan and can take you to the East Village, Soho, West Village, Chelsea, Time Square, Rockefeller Center and the southern part of Central Park. It's the best train! :)
access: Guests have access to the whole apartment.
interaction: This listing is for the whole apartment I will not be staying there. I will check in sporadically during your stay and if in town, during your stay, am accessible anytime.
house_rules: No smoking in apartment. No Pets allowed.  Please leave apartment as you found it.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
I live in NYC, I work in Oklahoma, but originally from Texas. I love to travel and meeting new people. Big tennis fan and movie buff. I'm a director/producer/writer of TV commercials, theater, film and web videos. I also am Executive Director of a short film festival, NYC PictureStart Film Festival as well as Founder/Executive Director of Tulsa American Film Festival. 

I have a small 1 bedroom apt in the Lower East Side in Manhattan. I rent out my apartment two ways - as a full on rental during the year when I am traveling, or as a shared situation for those traveling alone and want a safe, clean, cool place to crash while you are checking out NYC. The latter option is good for people looking for cheap place to stay while interning, here on business, or as a place to stay while looking for something more permanent. 

I'm very open minded, liberal, laid back and respectful. All welcome.

I rent just the small bedroom with kitchen use at breakfast from 7am to 10:30am. I leave some space in the refrigerator if you have snacks. I am often available to orient guests and to give advise on how to get around town by subway and bus. host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
We love to travel. When we travel we like to stay in a comfortable place that is clean, neat and sweet smelling, for a reasonable price. That's what we rent to you. We love city life but we also love outdoor adventures. We like keep up with all that's new and exciting around New York and we're happy to tell you where to find it. Want to hear the new young musicians that people are excited about or the promising new artists - we'll tell you about them. The best restaurants - ask us.
Want to take a break from the city we'll tell you about wilderness canoeing on the Delaware river - just an hour and a half's drive. We can tell you where to find the great salt water fishing with clean beautiful waters just an hour away from the city or how to take a one day trip by bus to ski in Vermont.


WHY WILLIAMSBURG?

Williamsburg is FABULOUS. It's fast growing and it's fast changing. It's hip. In the 1960's the new and exciting place where culture was blooming was Greenwich Village. In the 70's the SOHO neighborhood was where cheap industrial loft space were being turned into places where the adventurous could move to New York, live cheaply and make the new art, music, and culture. These days Williamsburg has that special chemistry of the New York that's constantly renewing itself.

summary: This is a street-level floor of a 4-story brownstone on a residential street. We live upstairs but it's private w/own entrance. Stairs lead to main house (behind door) but we don't enter. neighborhood_overview: Chelsea if a fun place. We are loaded with food options from markets to top notch restaurants and cafe's. There is something you will love to eat.  We have interesting and unusual museums such as a the Fashion institute, the Rubin, and the gallery district.  The parks are lovely and fun offering space and fresh air to ride, jog or relax as well as being host to many regular events, artists, green markets and food vendors.  The Highline is a wonderful place to view the city from a different perspective, have drink, relax, read and watch the life of NY happening. There are so many activities to participate in or view close by you wont be alone or bored. Try an evening at the Joyce dance theatre, the Mixers or discussions at the Rubin, workout groups at the Chelsea piers or a show at the Irish Reparatory all within a few blocks.
notes: I respect privacy utmost. A clean environment. I recycle  everything.  I do not use toxic chemicals.  I have serious allergies and so there are no scallop allowed in the flat at all.  Perfumed products may not be applies in the flat. If they are applies outside then usually they are so diminished by your return they are not an issue. Please be aware however that if you do use them and they cause a reaction that I will need to ask you to wash and not use them again. Wool can be worn out of the flat but not inside. Please have something to put your wool things into while in the flat.  I do recognize that this can be disruptive to you, but critical for my health.  I appreciate your consideration.
transit: Parking is available but can be complicate. There is a garage directly across the street from me. It is 24 hours and for a regular car costs about 25 dollars for 10 to 12 hours depending on the time.  There is free parking on my block from 7PM to 8AM Monday through Friday, and 7PM to 8AM Friday night to Monday morning. There is free parking to the west of me 7th avenue and to the west, everyday however finding a free space may be time consuming. You will also need to move your care twice a week if you are there long enough. It will be either Monday and Thursday or Tuesday and Friday each week from 9AM to 10:30Am that you will need to move it and stay in your car that entire time. Its a NY thing!
access: Guests are welcome to relax and enjoy the living room, dining area which can be a nice area to read or work in while having coffee or tea..., There is usually fresh coffee and tea at the ready as well as fruit and other snacks. You are welcome to use the kitchen lightly.
interaction: I love to meet my guests and get to know them. I respect their privacy and tolerance for interaction. I am happy to assist in planning or just having a nice chat.
house_rules: Primarily be a kind, open minded person. I do not allow any bigotry here. If you don't fit that criteria please do not reserve with me.  I am asthmatic so use of  any perfumed products must be restricted. Generally if they are applied outside of the flat I am OK but they cannot be applied in the flat. Please try to use non perfumed products completely. I am also allergic to wool and shellfish.  I appreciate your understanding and compliance with this situation.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Raised in Europe and Asia I love to host international guests and to travel abroad being hosted as well.
 
I have a home near Washington DC to which I often go. 
 
I love to entertain and do so frequently. I also host many programs in my home.
 
The eternal student I am always involved in learning something new. Currently a graduate student in psychology, art welding.
 
I speak a little German and Italian and ASL.

name: Sweet and Spacious Brooklyn Loft
summary: A true open-plan loft in a repurposed factory building with beautiful sunlight, a king bed and comfy double futon, fully stocked kitchen with dishwasher, washer and dryer, custom cedar sauna, bathroom with tub and shower, and lots of lounging spaces.
space: The apartment is an open-plan (Phone number hidden by Airbnb) sq. ft. loft (140 sq m) with 5 large windows providing bright sunlight all day, located in an old factory building with many of the original finishes including tin ceilings, wooden beams and columns, and white brick walls. Very few of these original factory loft buildings remain in the neighborhood, and this space is quite special. Located in the very center of Williamsburg: just two blocks from the Bedford L train and two blocks from McCarren park! Stellar restaurants, bars, nightlife, and shopping are all steps away. Manhattan is just a 5-10 minute ride on the L train. The loft has a fully stocked kitchen with fridge, oven, microwave, dishwasher, and everything you might need for cooking: great knives, pots and pans, a wide range of spices, kitchen tools, and a beautiful dining table.  There is a large bathroom, a custom cedar sauna for 5 (built by yours truly), a washer/dryer, and air conditioning.  For your entertainment

neighborhood_overview: We've lived here for over 10 years and watched as the neighborhood has transformed into the vibrant creative scene for which it has become renowned. When you arrive, you'll find a printout of our personal neighborhood favorite shops, restaurants, bars and more.
notes: Please note that our space is only available for stays of 30 nights or more. The  price for monthly rentals is discounted by 45% off of the listed per night rate.
transit: If arriving by plane, you can take a taxi from any of the major airports.  If arriving by bus or train into Manhattan, you can take any subway line downtown and connect to the L train to Brooklyn at 14th Street. We are located 2 short blocks from the Bedford Avenue L train stop (the first stop in Brooklyn). Parking is available on the street should you happen to have a car.
access: Travel toiletries are available in the bathroom in case you forgot anything at home. And, feel free to use any food items in the kitchen pantry and fridge.
interaction: We're available by text, phone, and email for any questions you may have during your stay. We love to share our knowledge of the neighborhood and city with you :-) Also, we have several neighbors on site available to assist with any questions or needs that may come up during your stay. If anything should happen to malfunction or break during your stay, the landlord and super are also available in the building. We'll provide you with everyone's contact info upon arrival.
house_rules: Please treat our home with love as you would your own :-) No smoking indoors and no pets unless discussed when booking the reservation.

We are a couple in our thirties who love to travel and explore.

neighborhood_overview: Just about everything you will ever need is within a few blocks of the apartment (typical Manhattan); pharmacy, hardware store, deli, laundry, etc. There are quite a few grocery stores/ supermarkets nearby, including Fairway, which carries gourmet and organic foods. Fresh direct also delivers to the area.  There's a good variety of restaurants nearby. You can get anything from a juicy, hand-formed burger, to curry dishes, to $1 homemade tamales on the street, to churrasco, to burritos, to sushi 'til 2am; I think you get the point.  The area is safe, parking spaces are available, and your car will be secure. People are very nice, and friendly. It is very neighborhood-y; hell, the crossing guard knows my name. It is more of a family neighborhood, but there are also many young people in the area because of the great number of schools nearby.  The apartment is conveniently located right down the street from City College and just 2 stops from Columbia, Barnard, Teachers College, Manhattan S
notes: this is a very old building and my place is very modest, but I like to keep it nice and clean.  The apartment is pretty quiet most of the time.

name: Lovely room 2 & garden; Best area, Legal rental
summary: Lovely room,  gorgeous garden, helpful host in beautiful, vibrant Park Slope.  Super safe & quiet, culturally rich,  excellent restaurants, Prospect Park.  This is a LEGAL rental. 2 minutes walk to 3 great subway lines.   Organic market, 6 gyms, by house. Please read;  then write me about your trip and needs.  Please do not  request reservation until I reply "YES".
space: Welcome to an historic and stunning 4-story Brooklyn house filled with light, color, artwork & lovely garden, in beautiful Park Slope!   Safe,  quiet, dynamic,  popular neighborhood (#1 in NY!)     Three excellent SUBWAYS (R, F, G) by house.  20 mins to Manhattan. LEGAL rental of  one bedroom on top "Guest" floor. Please write;  Wait until I reply "yes"  before you request reservation.    Discounts for long stays; I'm flexible.  The main floor is my office.   Enjoy the patio and  garden! This is a beautiful historic OLD  house, not modern,  so it has quirks of old houses, like creaky stairs.  Think about your travel preferences before you write me. THE BEDROOMS:   2  Quiet, cozy rooms on TOP  floor,  medium size,   with closets. 1 room --  2 twins or comfortable King (special mattress). neighborhood_overview: Neighborhood is wonderful, a great walking neighborhood.   Free concerts all summer, great restaurants and bars, music venues, Botanical garden, Brooklyn Museum, playgrounds, 4 gyms nearby.  Often ranked the # 1 neighborhood in NYC!
notes: There are 2 flights of stairs to your room.  Pack lightly, I have washing machine! Come and go as you wish.  Quiet in evenings.  Send me your personal email as soon as you reserve, so I can provide you with my excellent travel, house, and NYC booklet!
transit: 3 different subway lines, just 3 minutes walking.  Buses on the avenues.  Car parking on street.
access: Main floor is my office and work space and is private later at night.
interaction: My home  is best for  casual, flexible, not fussy,  and busy visitors.  Make yourself at home and let me know anything you need.  I'm busy but welcoming and helpful !
house_rules: Everyone must wear shoes NOT socks on my stairs. Sorry, no  children in rooms for safety.  Older kids can have their own room.  Please clean  your hair out of shower drain every day,  and off of the floor.  Put in garbage.   No hair dyes can be used in house.  No wipes of any kind, no sanitary products, no heavy papers, in the toilet.  Please use as little WATER as possible!   Do not ever open door for anyone, no exceptions.   I have a fantastic guide book; please read, print, and follow house rules! No problem to come in late. Please respect my neighbors -  be quiet but friendly outside.   Please FOLLOW RECYCLE RULES:   Paper is separate;  Metal plastic, glass and cartons  together . Do NOT UNPLUG  ANY PLUGS. Turn off fans, air conditioner, lights each day. Patio events with permission. Sorry, no TV for your use.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Hello, 
I will be welcoming and helpful,  while respecting your privacy.  I know a lot about NY & Brooklyn and love my neighborhood.  I'm especially interested in arts and music. 
I speak and understand several languages.  I work at home a lot,  on my main floor, and do prefer guests who are busy themselves, and casual,  low-key, trusting and flexible people.  
 It's an old house with quirks, (not a hotel!)  in a fantastic and quiet location.
Included: Laundry,  excellent coffee & breakfast foods, nice linens, big garden & BBQ,  fans, air conditioners.  
Some use of kitchen can be worked out.

name: Cute apt in artist's home
summary: We are renting a private basement apartment in our home. The apartment space is totally private, nothing shared. It has a separate bedroom, bathroom and kitchenette with mini fridge and coffee maker (there is no stove for cooking).  You will have use of a hair dryer. There are small windows in the bedroom and kitchenette area. The bathroom and kitchenette are all newly built. Full size bed sleeps 2 people. We cannot accommodate more than 2 people, sorry!
space: Our basement room with private bathroom and kitchenette is located in our home where we reside upstairs. There are custom-made artistic details throughout the apartment, including beautiful steel banister, thick maple wood bench, sculptural metal table and unique sculpture throughout. Interesting concave yellow bathroom tiles light up the bathroom. Bushwick is a vibrant community with lots of restaurants, bars, art galleries, cafes and street art. transit: Our house is a 7 min walk to the L train (Jefferson St stop); 15min train ride to Manhattan (East Village and Union Square.) We are also a 5 min walk to the M train (Central Ave stop); 15min train ride to Manhattan (Lower East Side, Soho, West Village, Midtown.) Also 5min ride on either train to Bedford Ave in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. NYC subways run 24hrs/day. The B60 bus stop is directly in front of the house which takes you straight to south Williamsburg. We are happy to provide you with directions and recommendations. You will be provided with a map of our favorite places within walking distance.
access: Travels access the space through a wonder contemporary art gallery called Gallery Petite. Enter through a beautiful metal and glass storefront made by the host and walk by ultra progressive art on the walls to the door that goes down to the basement apartment.
interaction: I live and work only a block away so I am almost always immediately available to meet your needs. I live upstairs in the building adjacent to the gallery spaces and my sculpture studio is a short block away.
house_rules: No smoking inside; please smoke outside only. Check in before 10pm. Try to be quiet with the front doors. Ask before using the laundry machines and plan to provide your own detergent. Separate recycling from your trash: paper and cardboard are separate from plastic, glass and metal. We appreciate if you take your trash outside in the bins provided. Please do have packages or mail sent to our house. Enjoy your stay!
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: While my wife Silvia and I have managed our airbnb rentals for several years together, I will now be the main contact in order to give her a break. So here is a little about me. I'm a metal sculptor, assemblage artist with a degree in Biochemistry, I love to make art, surf and play with my two young kids, eat good food and travel. But now that I'm a Dad, I don't  travel as much, so I let we the travelers come to me. The kids and I love going to the beach at Rockaway, art openings and going to cafes. You might spot my kids and I racing down the sidewalks in Bushwick on our skateboards.

neighborhood_overview: Historically, the Lower East Side was a stopping ground for immigrants who just arrived in NYC and was filled with tenements. There is an awesome Tenement Museum now on Orchard street, not far from my apartment. The Lower East Side has, in my opinion, two identities. The eastern side is very residential. The western, more in part is a hip, night time destinations with many bars, restaurants, galleries, cafes, independent shops, etc. My apartment is a couple of minutes from the hip part.  My particular street is very much in transition definitely going through gentrification. My block has now three renovated buildings, including mine and I suspect in a few years, will be completely different.  My immediate neighborhood is a mix of people - a real reflection of NYC diversity - Asian, Latin, Jewish, Black, young professionals, hipsters, artists, etc. It's a cool mix. The street is urban for sure but very safe. My building is filled with young professionals, creative types - one married co
notes: This is my personal apartment. It's not a business. It's not a hotel. It's not perfect. I host often and keep up with my place because of that. I try to keep it as clean as possible. However, it does have imperfections like anyone's home. If you expect perfection, it's best you book a hotel. :)
transit: F train, East Broadway stop is seconds away, very convenient and per my reviews, one of the things people love about my place.  The East Broadway stop is the last stop in Manhattan before it heads to Dumbo in Brooklyn The F train also goes up the center of Manhattan and can take you to the East Village, Soho, West Village, Chelsea, Time Square, Rockefeller Center and the southern part of Central Park. It's the best train! :)
access: Guests have access to the whole apartment.
interaction: As we will be sharing the apartment, interaction is a given. I will definitely give you as much privacy and quiet time as needed, but I am also always available for pleasant conversation and if have time, up for beers and hanging out.
house_rules: No smoking. No pets in apartment. No guests, especially overnight.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
I live in NYC, I work in Oklahoma, but originally from Texas. I love to travel and meeting new people. Big tennis fan and movie buff. I'm a director/producer/writer of TV commercials, theater, film and web videos. I also am Executive Director of a short film festival, NYC PictureStart Film Festival as well as Founder/Executive Director of Tulsa American Film Festival. 

I have a small 1 bedroom apt in the Lower East Side in Manhattan. I rent out my apartment two ways - as a full on rental during the year when I am traveling, or as a shared situation for those traveling alone and want a safe, clean, cool place to crash while you are checking out NYC. The latter option is good for people looking for cheap place to stay while interning, here on business, or as a place to stay while looking for something more permanent. 

I'm very open minded, liberal, laid back and respectful. All welcome.

name: ENJOY Downtown NYC!
summary: Please contact BEFORE sending reservation request.  Private Room with room for two, queen size bed in BASEMENT 3-bedroom apartment in bohemian East Village neighborhood. Restaurants, shops, live-music, night-life are all within blocks!   Awesome area for exploring downtown and seeing how locals live.   Apartment is in back of building and quiet for sleeping.   Flexible check-in and you can come and go as you please.  I love hosting travelers and will provide as much information as you want!
space: You get your own room with comfortable queen size bed in 8x10 space.  Has plenty of storage & desk with fan & air conditioner during warmer months.  Good for short and long stays.   You will share the kitchen & bathroom with other guests and my roommate. Best for budget travelers looking for a safe, clean, convenient home base to experience NYC. Again it is in a three bedroom BASEMENT apartment with little sunlight.  FYI:  you must enter through building courtyard to get to apartment - so you will pass recycling & the garbage room. Experienced Host - ask me any questions you may have and read some of the reviews. Hundreds of guests have enjoyed NYC from this humble abode, and I have made it quite comfy but it is a simple space.   If you have any questions or concerns before or during your stay please communicate!  For travelers wanting to be in an awesome neighborhood for an affordable price, this is one of the best options out there.  --------------------------------

neighborhood_overview: Long Island City is the hottest neighborhood in all of NYC. Beautiful historic block, lined with old trees and turn of the century residential townhouse architecture. The neighborhood has a great number of places to eat, including Italian, Peruvian, Thai and Chinese food, and the typical American Diner (COURT SQUARE DINER) thats open 24 hours. The LIC CORNER CAFE, around the corner, serves homemade pastries and sandwiches. LIC MARKET serves the freshest most innovative food in Queens. Film & TV crews are always filming on our block. Time-Out Magazine rated it "The 3rd Best Block in all of NYC!" We are a 12 minute walk to the new Gantry State Park, a $30 million Riverwalk Park with stunning views of Manhattan, and to the new Ferry Service, which takes you to Brooklyn , Manhattan and Astoria .
notes: Towels, Hairdryer, Soap, Shampoo provided.
transit: Very convenient to Manhattan, which is only one stop away! 3 lines( E, M, 7,) go into Manhattan,one line ( G ) goes to Brooklyn (Williamsburg and beyond). Airport connections from JFK, La Guardia and Newark are easy (JFK and La Guardia are the fastest). There is street parking in the evenings only, although you can easily park at a car garage 2 blocks away.
access: Direct access under stoop to hallway that leads to your private room. A dedicated, luxurious bathroom is next to room.  In the rear, a professionally landscaped garden can be used to enjoy breakfast & quiet time only. Smoking allowed in rear garden (till 10pm).
interaction: Only if they want. I enjoy and respect our mutual privacy. I will be present during most stays but I do often travel, and will leave the house either with my partner (Cristian ) or a qualified, trusted live-in House Sitter.
house_rules: No smoking inside. No outside guests.   No cooking. Appreciate taking off street shoes inside room. We have a dog, so no pets please.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Photographer/Real Estate Developer. 
I enjoy NYC tremendously but I love traveling and have visited
over 45 countries. My house is filled with artwork from those travels.
I work my art photography business from my home studio, in a restored 1890 landmark townhouse with all the modern amenities.
My house has been used for filming scenes for Sex & The City, The Sopranos, Gossip Girl & White Collar.
My photography column,"Orestes'LIC", appears every month in the local paper.
I love Asian, Spanish & Cuban food, along with a good bottle of red wine.
Talking about travel, art, design and photography are my favorite subjects.
Sorry,I dont shop a lot or know where the best electronics bargains are located ! 
I love giving great walking tour information of different parts of NYC, and show you non-touristy places to eat authentic food in the area.
I will provide you the privacy level you require to make your stay is as comfortable as possible.
Enjoy a clean, quiet, stylish place to stay, only 7 minutes from Manhattan!

space: A beautiful room for two people in a historical four stories brownstone with original wood details from the 1800s, on a lovely quiet street, one block away from subway, laundry mat, supermarket, and shopping. Cafes, restaurants, and wine bars all around. Guests will have use of a fully functional, modern, all stainless steel kitchen on the upstairs floor. The room is WiFi ready.  It has a queen size iron bed, an antique mirror bureau and a dresser, a ship steam trunk, a sofa, a round table where you can eat at, two large wall closets, one with drawers and shelves. The Blue Room has its own private bathroom, so you don't have to share your bathroom with anyone. Your bathroom is right outside the room, it has a claw foot bathtub.  The mattress has been recently changed. The room is WiFi ready. neighborhood_overview: We are in New York! And Brooklyn is the new hip place of the city, with plenty of culture and shopping during the day and an exciting night life: restaurants, bars, clubs, cinemas, theaters, museums, art galleries, the Brooklyn Academy of Music with a full program of events 365 days a year, a fantastic park -Prospect Park- and so many different neighborhoods to explore. Our neighborhood is called Bedford Stuyvesant: it is African American, Caribbean, and African, with plenty of music, a plethora of European and ethnic restaurants and coffee shops, wine bars, and music venues. It is surrounded by Crown Heights on the south, Clinton HIll on the West and Williamsburg on the North. Nearby are the Brooklyn Museum with the seond largest Egyptian collection in the world, the Brooklyn Children Museum, The Brooklyn Botanical Garden, Prospect Park, The Brooklyn Library, The Brooklyn Academy Of Music, and the Brooklyn Bridge.
notes: Linens and towels are provided by us.  Once a week sheets and towels are changed and bedrooms, bathrooms and kitchen are cleaned.  On a  daily basis please clean after yourself and leave the sink in the kitchen clean. Be considerate of the next guest.  -Cleaning fee for the first week: 35$, which is paid directly to Airbnb at the time of reservation. If you rent the room for longer than a week, cleaning fee is $25 per week (due to us weekly, in cash). Cleaning is compulsory. We do not allow guests to clean their own rooms.  There are three laundromats right around the house, a public library two roads down, plenty of coffee shops, restaurants, and wine bars. A post office and two supermarkets are also very close by. Before you book, 2 things:  1) CATS ON THE PREMISES!! Not in your rooms of course, but they are freely allowed to go around the house, so you might meet them! And their fluffy hair! Did you just read above that we have four cats? You will meet them, so if you are even sligh
transit: Bedford Stuyvesant is close to both JFK airport and La Guardia airport and the Long Island Railroad, which gives you quick access to Long Island.  We are close to Clinton Hill, Fort Greene, Williamsburg, Park Slope, Downtown Brooklyn, Brooklyn Heights, and Dumbo.  We are 20 minutes away from Manhattan on the blue line (C and A trains). Taxi cabs are available (both metro cabs and private taxis) Also there is a bicycle depot close to our house, on Nostrand Ave and on Albany Avenue, just around the corner.
access: Living room, parlor, kitchen and stoop are accessible to guests. We live on the ground floor and have our bedrooms on the top floor.
interaction: We live on the premises so we are always available to help you with info and to make your sojourn more comfortable in any way we can. Other than that we live you alone yo enjoy your privacy.

Leaving the keys in the room, a message to us that you have left, and the entrance doors open behind you, IS UNACCEPTABLE. name: Cozy 1BD on Central Park West in New York City
summary: Spend your time in this pre-war brownstone apt on Central Park West.   Cozy. Cool. Very quiet. Faces the back. Engage in the excitement that is New York, but rest in this little oasis.
space: Enjoy this cozy pre-war brownstone right on Central Park! I'm a big traveller, so the place is artfully decorated with mementos from India, Brazil, Japan, and Spain. summary: Located in the heart of Park Slope, a safe, family neighborhood, we are right across the street from beautiful JJ Byrne Playground / Old Stone House and a short walk to the subway, Prospect Park, the Sunday farmer's market, Whole Foods, and incredible restaurants and bars. Our 2-bedroom, 2-bathroom duplex has amazing light, a rear balcony and a large south-facing roof deck. With toddler beds, a crib, a washer-dryer and plenty of space, our place is perfect for families.
space: Our place is a relaxed and quiet refuge from the city! With two floors, incredible natural light, and lots of plants, we have plenty of space to accommodate families in comfort. The large master bedroom upstairs opens directly out onto the south-facing deck, where in season you can enjoy views of the Freedom Tower and Statue of Liberty while eating straight out of the garden! The open kitchen / living room area is perfect for hanging out, and opens to a north-facing terrace (think Rear Window) where you can drink your morning coffee. An airy children's bedroom can comfortably sleep two. A daybed under the stairs can accommodate an adult. We have copious closet and storage space for you, and a washer-dryer in-house to keep you fresh on your journey. For long stays, cleaning service can be arranged.

neighborhood_overview: We are in the heart of Park Slope, a truly beautiful, safe, family-friendly neighborhood with a thriving food scene and endless options for adults and kids. We live across the street from recently-renovated JJ Byrne Playground, the Old Stone House, and Washington Park. A farmer's market is held here on Sundays, in addition to regular street fairs and events. Prospect Park is an easy 4 block walk straight up 3rd street (or take a Citibike if you prefer), and the Brooklyn Museum and Brooklyn Botantical Garden are both within walking distance. 5th avenue is a wildly diverse restaurant row - Stone Park Cafe (considered one of the best in Brooklyn) is right on our corner. Local clubs like Barbes and Union Hall offer eclectic music almost every night. You could spend an entire vacation within walking distance of the apartment!
transit: We are a 5-7 minute walk to the Union Street R train (just one station away from Atlantic Avenue station where you can access all major subway lines), and the same from the 9th street F-G line. There is a Citibike station on the corner, which is a fantastic and convenient way to get around the City. For drivers, street parking is not too bad on our block, but for full convenience take advantage of two garages, each of which is located a block away.

neighborhood_overview: The East Village is perhaps the neighborhood that has retained the most character and authenticity in all of Manhattan. It's very diverse, lively and accessible. Without question, it has the highest percentage of amazing independently-run and reasonably-priced restaurants, bars, clubs and cafes. It also has a ton of independent boutiques, vintage shops, record shops, book stores, and art galleries. It's one of the few places in America where you might be able to walk for a few blocks without running into a single multinational McDonald's, Subway, KFC, etc.
notes: Just to be clear, we are renting rooms out in our 3 bedroom home, during times in which one or more of us are traveling. If you're looking for a slightly less personal and unique hospitality experience, perhaps a hotel room would be a better fit! What staying with us will give you is the experience of what it feels like to live in one of the best apartments in one of the most interesting neighborhoods in the world. But if it's amenities and a concierge service that you require, this may not be for you.
transit: The 2nd Avenue F Train is 4 minutes away, the Astor Place 6 train is 8 minutes away and the 1st Avenue L Train is 8 minutes away. There are express buses running up and downtown on 1st and 2nd Avenues. And there are numerous Citibike locations nearby. In short, it's a great place to land when you come to visit NYC.
access: Guests have access to private fire escape/terrace of the room, back deck, rooftop, kitchen, living room, bathroom, etc.
interaction: Regardless of whether I'm traveling or not, I'm generally very accessible via text, email or other apps. We are all helpful and pleasant but quite busy in our own lives. We just ask that guests are respectful of our time and space and we will do the same!
house_rules: Cleanliness, respect of other's privacy, keeping noise levels down at night/in the morning and communication are important.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: I work as a freelance photographer and run an arts non-profit, Slideluck.  I am busy, but social, respectful, clean, often out at night, cook frequently and travel a lot.

name: SpaHa Loft: Enormous and Bright
summary: Our luxury loft occupies the entire second floor of an old warehouse with high ceilings, lots of windows, 4 bedrooms & 2 bathrooms. It's located next to a small park on a very quiet block. Supermarket is next door, and the subway five minutes away.
space: ABSOLUTELY NO SMOKING! PLEASE NOTE RATE VARIES DEPENDING ON MONTH/SEASON AND IS BASED ON 4 PEOPLE. A SECURITY DEPOSIT IS REQUIRED, AND  THERE IS A $150 CLEANING FEE. AVAILABLE ALL YEAR! ALL UTILITIES & WIFI INCLUDED. CHECKOUT TIME IS 10:00 AM. Soak up the Latin beat of exciting SpaHa (Manhattan's Spanish Harlem) in this 2000+ square foot luxury loft taking up the entire second floor of an old warehouse that has been renovated with care. With 12ft ceilings, the custom windows let in tons of light.   The loft has four bedrooms (2 with queen beds, 2 with 2 twins).  In true loft fashion, the walls don't quite reach the ceilings, but it's great for families or groups of friends on an outing to New York, or maybe even looking for a place to settle for a while. There are two bathrooms, two enormous walk-in closets, and a laundry room with washer-dryer.  The kitchen has everything you need, including a microwave oven, coffee maker and toaster. name: BLUE TRIM GUEST HOUSE
summary: A well-loved guest room in a bright, spacious flat: our family home of ten years, a nurturing destination for global travelers.
space: Over tea, coffee or whisky (as your schedule goes), we'll get acquainted with one another's laughter and lives at a dining table which enjoys sweeping views of the city. We're respectful of boundaries and hope only to be of help while you're here. The layout of the apartment provides spaciousness, as the guest room pairs with a full private bathroom to form a distinct and sunny 'wing' for your quiet relaxation. Your windows face the rising sun, and blackout shades installed ensure a good night's rest no matter how sensitive to light you may be as a sleeper. There's ample closet and drawer space, electrical outlets within easy reach. As a launchpad to the larger city, we're perfectly positioned between JFK airport and Manhattan, making arrival a breeze, and exploration a joy. But you won't need to go far to find out why Brooklyn has a global reputation. If questions, please inquire - we look forward to introducing you to a city we adore.

neighborhood_overview: The adjacent Brooklyn neighborhoods of Fort Greene and Clinton Hill contain a sampling of the best the borough has to offer. Historic districts, a hilltop park designed by Olmsted & Vaux, cutting-edge art and up-and-coming chefs, a pedigreed college and a repurposed hub for homegrown industry—all can be found here. And getting to, from and around the area has never been easier: the many subway lines servicing Atlantic Terminal deliver you to BAM's doorstep, and the G and C subway lines make stops in both neighborhoods. Add the more than 20 Citi Bike stations available throughout the area, and you have what may be Brooklyn's ideal day trip. The two neighborhoods' elegant rows of brownstones are popular with film crews—you may well stumble across a production in progress as you wander along tree-lined Willoughby Avenue or stroll past the boutiques and restaurants on Dekalb Avenue. Spend some time here, and you'll come to see that, along with the area's physical beauty, its charm lies in
transit: Street parking is very frequently available, and Citi Bike stations are generously distributed in the area (the nearest is 1 block away). The C train is on our block, the G train is two blocks away, and almost every other train line (including LIRR, for easy Hamptons daytripping) is a 15 minute stroll away at the Atlantic Terminal. Buses are also close at hand, with several lines serving the streets adjacent to us. But not so close that we have to hear them.
access: Our home is your home.
interaction: We're here to help however we can.
house_rules: Check-in time is flexible. Check-out is 10 am. Pets are not allowed. Smoking is not allowed. Children are absolutely welcome, and should be mentioned in advance. Visitors are likewise welcome, but no overnight guests, please. We're a shoes-off home, kindly remove yours in our entrance hall. For our cancellation policy, please refer to our listing details.

summary: Stay in my bright guest bedroom, with use of your own private bathroom, in a beautiful, shared, 1750 square foot (163 square meters), sun drenched, loft-like apartment on the 4th floor (walk-up) of a Brooklyn Brownstone overlooking Fort Greene Park.
space: This is a private bedroom with exclusive use of a hallway bathroom in a shared apartment. The apartment is on the 4th floor (walk-up) of a historic Brooklyn Brownstone fronting Fort Greene Park. It has an open kitchen with a large butcher block island ideal for cooking with friends, and a private planted roof deck to enjoy early morning coffee or an evening glass of wine, all located in historic Fort Greene, one of Brooklyn's best neighborhoods! The bedroom is cozy, with plenty of room for singles or couples, with both short-term and medium-term availability, and is only a short train ride to Manhattan - 1 stop on the Q/B, 2 stops on the F, or 4 stops on the C - and walking distance to the Brooklyn Bridge. I've lived in the neighborhood for over 13 years, and can provide you with any and all advice, maps, or guides that you should need during your stay. neighborhood_overview: Fort Greene is an iconic Brownstone Brooklyn neighborhood. Fort Greene is a beautiful, historic, and diverse neighborhood that is very walkable, with many local restaurants, cafes, and shops, a farmers' market on Saturday mornings all year long, and a lot to offer in terms of the arts (Brooklyn Academy of Music, Irondale Center, Pratt Institute Sculpture Garden) and unique mom & pop shopping and dining (Brooklyn Flea, and the 3 retail strips of Myrtle, Dekalb, and Fulton).
transit: Fort Greene has great public transit access. The apartment has great subway access:  10 minute walk to the C train, the Q train (1 stop to Manhattan, 2 stops to Union Square, 4 stops to Times Square, 30 minutes to Coney Island), the B train (1 stop to Chinatown, 2 stops to Soho, 3 stops to West Village), the R train (3 stops to lower Manhattan and the Staten Island Ferry), and the G train subway lines (to Williamsburg or Long Island City). Just a bit further, about a 12-15 minute walk to the 4, 5, 2, 3, D, and the Long Island Railroad (trains to the Hamptons and Fire Island ferries). NEARBY SUBWAYS G at Fulton St (0.4 miles) B, Q, R at DeKalb Av (0.5 miles) C at Lafayette Av (0.5 miles) 2, 3, 4, 5 at Nevins St (0.5 miles) B, D, N, R, Q, 2, 3, 4, 5 at Atlantic Av (0.6 miles)
access: Guests can have access to the entire house (except for the master bedroom and master bath). Along with their own private bedroom and hallway bathroom, guests have full use of kitchen, living room, washer/dryer, roof deck, and all shared areas.
interaction: Guests will have their own set of keys and can come and go on their own at any time they like. We have pretty busy schedules and are coming and going a lot, but one of us will always be there to greet guests and check them in, and can offer any advice on the neighborhood or the city as requested. We are also always available via text during guests' stay, and if we are not around, we will quickly respond via text for any questions guest have. REGARDING CHECK-IN: We have listed a check-in time of 6pm due to our work schedules. We can sometimes do earlier for weekend check-ins. We will always do our best to accommodate modified check-in times, but cannot guarantee it. Please ask us prior to booking if you will need an early check-in, and we will do our best to accommodate you.
house_rules: Thanks for booking at Fort Greene Retreat on the Park. No smoking is allowed in the apartment, though you may smoke on the roof deck. If you are going to smoke on the roof deck, please bring up a small plate or ashtray with you. Please, no ashing or discarding cigarette butts in the pots or planters or on the furniture, brick or bluestone. Thank you.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Ben and I split our time between Fort Greene, Brooklyn and Hudson, NY. I've lived in Fort Greene for over 16 years, and am an urban planner who does economic development and neighborhood revitalization work. Ben is an attorney in the public sector.

We spend many of our weekends at our 2nd home in the historic, small town of Hudson, New York, 2 hours north of NYC by train in the Hudson Valley.  We fixed up a 3-family house built in 1834,  and love to host friends and guests up there to experience the town and everything the Hudson Valley has to offer.

We enjoy running, hiking, and travel, and recently spent two weeks in Tanzania to climb Mount Kilimanjaro and go on safari.

neighborhood_overview: After walking all day downtown in the crowded streets, when I get out at my subway stop uptown I feel happy to be in my neighborhood, calmer, more friendly, lively and spacious. I walk home and I finally relax, I feel I am in the City, 20 minutes away from Colombus Circle…. but yet in my lovely quiet home. The neighborhood has become gentrified, there are now lots of new lovely restaurants and coffee shops. Some Art Galleries and new stores. My Gym is at 158th street, a great and inexpensive giant club. The supermarket is across Broadway, two blocks away. Fairways is at 134th street and for major food shopping is the best! On 145th there is my Bikrham Yoga club, the farmacy, the hardware sore, a library…. I find everything I need close by.
notes: For cooking, there is now a brand new double plate induction hotplate and a big multi function microwave. No GAS stove. The injection plate is super fast.

neighborhood_overview: (Source Wikipedia) Park Slope is considered one of New York City's most desirable neighborhoods. In 2010, it was ranked number 1 in New York by New York, citing its quality public schools, dining, nightlife, shopping, access to public transit, green space, safety, and creative capital, among other aspects. It was named one of the "Greatest Neighborhoods in America" by the American Planning Association in 2007, "for its architectural and historical features and its diverse mix of residents and businesses, all of which are supported and preserved by its active and involved citizenry." In December 2006, Natural Home magazine named Park Slope one of America's ten best neighborhoods based on criteria including parks, green spaces and neighborhood gathering spaces; farmers' markets and community gardens; public transportation and locally owned businesses; and environmental and social policy.

James, Born Thai, Latin Ideya, Geido Sushi and Anarchy are the restaurants we frequent , but are only a few of the many that are a short walk away. summary: My apartment has been called cozy, warm and comfortable.  It's updated, spacious apartment located in a popular Brooklyn neighborhood. Great for spending time at home, but close to restaurants, bars, shops and transportation, too.
space: I believe that I'd found the perfect location and neighborhood when I bought and renovated this 2-family brownstone in 2004. The House ------------- As a visual artist, natural light is very important to me, and I find traditional brownstones to be dark. So I had a gut renovation and added large picture windows to make the space open, bright and airy.  The renovation also included the complete update of all electrical, plumbing and heating systems. Central air conditioning was added, too. The upstairs consists of the living room (with the large, north-facing picture window, overlooking the backyard garden below), the kitchen that's open to the living room with stone counter tops, modern appliances, and gas range, and a dining room/office in the front of the house facing Dean Street. neighborhood_overview: Living in this house, in Bushwick for 12 years, we have really seen this neighborhood change from a small progressive art scene to a full blown art movement. Bushwick is the center of street art, graffiti  and murals.  It is  a popular destination of the New York City Free walking Tours. Bushwick graffiti and street art tours happen daily as well as many artists run art galleries, cafes and bars.
transit: Easy to get around in Bushwick. Our home is situated at a bus stop on the B60 bus line that leads directly to south Williamsburg. Also 5-10 min walk to the L train that goes directly into Manhattan  and crosses Manhattan to connect with many other subway trains. We're a 5 min walk to the JMZ subway lines.
access: You access the building at the front door where there is a small entry, to your immediate left is the door to the apartment. Guests can easily access the two art galleries and the laundry facility through the back room of the galleries.
interaction: I live and work nearby so I am very available. My sculpture studio is one block away. My art gallery is adjacent to our home and I live upstairs from the apartment. Also in the neighborhood, many venues like  restaurants cafés and homeowners, have my decorative artistic  metal work. If you're interested in visiting these places send me a message and I'll give you the addresses.
house_rules: No smoking inside; please smoke outside only. Try to be quiet with the front doors. Ask before using the laundry machines and plan to provide your own detergent. Separate recycling from your trash: paper and cardboard are separate from plastic, glass and metal. We appreciate if you take your trash outside in the bins provided. Please do have packages or mail sent to our house. Enjoy your stay!
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: While my wife Silvia and I have managed our airbnb rentals for several years together, I will now be the main contact in order to give her a break. So here is a little about me. I'm a metal sculptor, assemblage artist with a degree in Biochemistry, I love to make art, surf and play with my two young kids, eat good food and travel. But now that I'm a Dad, I don't  travel as much, so I let we the travelers come to me. The kids and I love going to the beach at Rockaway, art openings and going to cafes. You might spot my kids and I racing down the sidewalks in Bushwick on our skateboards.

neighborhood_overview: Restaurants:  Near the house, I love La Loteria and on Seventh Avenue and Bedford for "new Mexican" food; Rafele for Italian including the great fritto misto and caponata, excellent house made pastas. Fifty at 50 Commerce for "new American".  Taco Mahal on Seventh Ave just south of Bleecker, east side of street – Indian inspired tacos and basmati rice bowl Bob White Counter – just south of Taco Mahal – small sit down restaurant that does take out. $13 fried chicken or fried catfish with a side of NY’s best mac & cheese; artisanal liquor at the bar; cheap happy hour Masala Times – Bleecker just east of Sixth Ave – sit down or take out, excellent lamb biryani, full of Indian NYU students further afield: Esquina on Lafayette Street for Mexican food; Veselka on Second Avenue and Ninth Street for Ukrainian (get the meat borsht and the short rib pierogi); Jean Georges near Lincoln Center is great value, though not cheap, look for their late night and weekend brunch prix fixe for good values.
notes: Please note that the house comes with my two cats Mashia and Lulu, lovely and friendly half-brothers who are indoor-outdoor cats. They do their business in a network of gardens they can climb into from the back patio (but we can't!) No litter box hassles. I provide cat food, they eat 2 -4 cans a day and have a water dispenser and a kibble dispenser. But they do need to have some cat food opened for them daily. If your schedule does not allow for this,  housekeeper can do it at a small additional charge.
transit: 5 minutes from two different subway stops (1 train at Houston and Varick and A, C, E, D and F trains at West Fourth Street and Sixth Avenue. Citibikes at Sixth and Bleecker. Hudson bike path minutes away for running, blading and cycling.
access: Guests are renting the entire house and have access to the entire house including private roof deck and private rear patio.  Owner is absent when the house is rented but can answer questions by email or phone. Guests are of course given keys to the house. Please note that the two cats roam around the house except the red bedroom.
interaction: House is for renters alone during rental. No interaction with owner during rental except by email or telephone, unless owner is called upon to show how something works or must pick up an important piece of mail. Usually owner travels while house is rented.
house_rules: Check in 11 am but earlier is possible if there are no guests the night before; not before 9 am please. Renters  of the house are expected to feed the two house cats. Renters are expected to leave the house "broom clean" and no dirty dishes. Ask about film shoots and special events.

name: Williamsburg—Steps To Subway, Private Bath&Balcony
summary: Thoughtfully designed modern luxury two-storey condo situated mere steps from the subway. Features a private balcony w/ skyline view, tons of privacy, a large & modern bedroom & private bathroom. Truly a very large apartment for NYC standards.  Situated in Williamsburg, one of NYC's best & most desirable & fun neighborhoods. Plus, lots of fun perks: Japanese bidet toilet, tons of natural light but remote-control blinds when you want darkness, central A/C and heat, and an actual pinball machine!
space: (Pssst... Quick favor if you're thinking about booking: Please message me first to confirm, and also please read the entire listing as it likely answers any questions you may have. Thanks!)  --  Hi, I'm Seth. I'm here to make sure you have the best stay in New York possible. Looking to make this trip special? Let me know and I can help you get the most out of the hidden NYC that most tourists don't see. My place is situated in Williamsburg (undoubtedly the city's most fun and one of its most desirable neighborhoods) and is conveniently located just steps to the L line of the subway (it seriously couldn't be closer). It's a two-story duplex, with tons of space and privacy. I stay upstairs in what is basically a separate apartment, ensuring tons of privacy. It really is huge by NYC standards and, as my reviews say, it is actually even bigger than the pictures seem to suggest. The place includes: -Your own bathroom, complete with a Japanese bidet toilet and rainfall shower. -A spacious be

neighborhood_overview: Williamsburg has become world-famous for its fun, bars, restaurants, music venues, and general (once-)bohemian atmosphere. It still has a bit of graffiti and grit and is full of vibrant ethnic enclaves but is very safe and you simply won't find a younger, funner place in NYC. The apartment is steps to great restaurants (probably the best in the city), bars (definitely the best in the city), cafes, and anything else you could want.  Within a few minutes' walk you'll find: a huge arcade bar, a whiskey-slash-grilled-cheese bar, the most famous steakhouse in the country, dirt-cheap dives, incredible speakeasy cocktail bars, and the best pizza place in NYC.
notes: Please have a great time! And even though the area is lively and a lot of fun, the apartment itself is VERY quiet, in case that's a concern. Oh, and it's a walk-up/no elevator. All guests must be able to climb stairs with their bags. Same day guests must message me before Instant Booking to confirm availability, and checkin may be later than the listed time if we can make it work. Through Spring of 2020, the L train (nearest subway) will be undergoing long-term maintenance, resulting in slightly longer waits late at night and on weekends. The trains will still be running (the "L Train Shutdown" you may have heard about was actually canceled), and should be operating normally on weekdays, making the impact minimal to non-existant. Still, guests should be aware of this!
transit: The subway (L train) is literally around the corner (you don't even need to cross the street) and is quick and very safe—even late at night. You can get just about anywhere in the city in minutes. Union Square is about 10 minutes away, the East Village about 7 minutes. It really is about as convenient a location as you'll find for getting around.  We also have several CitiBike bike-share stations within steps of the building. For $10 a day (or a longer-term subscription), you get unlimited access to these bikes, parked throughout the entire city.  The neighborhood itself is also very walkable, with tons to do, eat, shop, and drink in the immediate vicinity. Be like the locals and walk!
access: Guests have access to an enormous and beautiful apartment in a great part of town, steps from the subway. Your private room has a private balcony, and is on a completely separate floor from where I sleep (meaning tons of privacy). You have your own bathroom, access to the kitchen, living room, and pretty much whatever else you like. You can come and go as you please, 24 hours a day, and you won't disturb me. I also offer free laundry with overnight drop-off service for guests staying at least six nights.
interaction: That's up to you! If you'd rather I didn't exist, I understand. If you want to grab a beer and talk about your trip and getting the most out of NYC, I'm happy to (assuming I'm not slammed with work)! There are also occasions when I have to travel at the last minute. So if I have to skip town for work, I apologize, and hope you enjoy the private apartment!
house_rules: -All guests must read the full listing (particularly the sections labeled "The Space" and "Other things to note") BEFORE booking. You may need to click a button to expand the text, but please do so. You'll see why I ask at the end (there's a bit of a code phrase in there.) Beyond that, it's all pretty much common sense! -Even if Instant Book is on, please read the entire listing before booking and message me that all looks good. You'll see why I ask at the end! (And please don't be surprised there are stairs!) -Before booking, please fill out your profile and add a real photo! And please message me a bit about yourself and the nature of your trip. -Please take shoes off inside. It's just better that way. -Please don't smoke inside. You have a balcony for this, but please close the door so smoke doesn't drift inside and don't throw your butts down below (people live down there!) -Guests may not receive mail or packages. summary: Beautiful 2 Bedroom Apartment, Great for Groups as large as 7.  Fully restored Apartment in a Brooklyn Brownstone.  Conveniently located 4 blocks from the Express train into the city.  All the features of home, make your meals in the equipped kitchen then relax in the large living. The Brownstone is located in the Stuyvesant Heights, Brooklyn a beautiful neighborhood rich in history and culture.  Please review all guest info after booking. Key entry, directions and a guide are available :-)
space: Welcome to The Stuydio SPEND YOUR HOLIDAYS IN NYC! MODERN TWO FULL SIZE BEDROOMS THIRD FLOOR OF BROWNSTONE  This space has been featured in The New York Times, San Francisco Chronicle, and Bloomberg Financial. Our large two bedroom apartment is located inside a restored Brownstone.  Very Large Space, 1000sqft!  From the moment you walk in the Brownstone you are swept away by the rich colors and the old world charm. Your modern apartment has all the features of home.  You can make your meals in the full kitchen, relax in the large airy living room, take in a nice soak in the jetted tub and just be happy on your VACATION!   The Brownstone is set on a historic tree lined block in Stuyvesant Heights, Brooklyn. Come on you know you want to give your vacation the finishing touch, join us! From the architecture of Magnus Dahlander to the former home of Jackie Robinson.  Here the church bells ring as you walk alot the blocks and take in the history.   New restaurants and cafes throughout the neighborhood, what do you like to eat? Southern American, Indian, Japanese, French, Italian take your pick.

transit: We are located between three subway stations: A- Utica C- Ralph J-Broadway (7 blocks but, a very scenic train, see all three bridges and the view across Manhattan) Lyft and Uber are super useful but, I dont recommend using them to the AIRPORT, they will over charge you.  I have a service that you can pay cash to if you need a taxi to the airport, its not more than $35-40 There are subway maps in the hallway if needed

house_rules: House Rules -No Smoking Please…some people have allergies.  You may smoke outside downstairs "outside the gate on the sidewalk" no exceptions  -No Shoes..... there is a shoe rack for you outside the door please ALL shoes there. The floor loves socks or slippers - This is our home and we live downstairs with small children, please keep noise down. -ABSOLUTELY NO Parties, Loud Romps, Jumping Up and Down on Floors. If the manager has to ask for you to be quiet due to any of these things you will be asked to Leave. There is NO EXCEPTION to this rule -Please Conserve Energy Use lamps… Turn lights and heat off when leaving  -We are sharing this space with wonderful people all over the world, please keep it nice so others may enjoy as much as you have.

name: Modern Brooklyn Apt., August sublet
summary: Seeking responsible and considerate sublet tenant for 1 month (Aug 1–Sept 3). Asking $3000/month—that's only $100/day—a RARE FIND for all this! All utilities, including wifi and cable, are included.
space: Don't think of this modern 1-bedroom apartment as a stranger's residence; it feels more like a suite in a small boutique hotel — even though it's actually my home when I'm not traveling on research assignments as a travel writer. (I won't seem like a stranger once we connect.)  This clean and well-maintained "suite" is stylish, yet comfortable (it has actually been a set for TV, film, and commercials), and is fully-equipped with wireless Internet, a state-of-the-art home entertainment system, and plenty of kitchen gadgets at your disposal if you are culinarily inclined. Oh, and the queen-sized bed and jacuzzi-fitted tub are quite lovely too. Adding to the convenience are washer/dryer, iron, garment steamer, and a dishwasher. Also, the sofa in the living room pulls out to a full-size bed, so the entire suite can sleep up to four comfortably. neighborhood_overview: It's full of energy and character.
notes: I'm often asked about the safety of the neighborhood. Harlem has changed a lot in the past several years. It is safe to walk around day or night, alone or in a group.  The security deposit will be refunded as long as the house rules are followed. I dont have many rules. The two most important of these rules: You absolutely MUST keep the shared bathroom clean. This means cleaning out the drain trap after every shower whether you wash your hair or not. This means not leaving hair on the floor of the bathroom. And this means not leaving the bathroom mirror dirty after every use. The second important rule is following the recycling rules. I don't want to keep your deposit. This is not some way for me to make more money. I genuinely want you to feel relaxed and welcome in my home. Some rules are necessary for good co-habitation, even short term. Unfortunately, having a fine seems to make people more responsible.

name: Sunny 2-story Brooklyn townhouse w deck and garden
summary: Our home is a beautifully renovated, bright and sunny house in a great Brooklyn neighborhood. The duplex layout includes a large open kitchen, living room and entry foyer, 3 bedrooms upstairs with master bath, a large deck and peaceful backyard -- plus we're close to great shops, parks, and cultural attractions.
space: The downstairs space includes the entry foyer, living room with working fireplace and bathroom, plus a large and sunny chef's kitchen with large dining area. Our large backyard has a large open grass area, artist studio/shed, and garden. A large sunny deck off the kitchen is great for outdoor meals. There is a washer/dryer, dishwasher, and wireless internet. We have a 7 year old and a 10 year old so the house is perfect for families. We have a bunk bed and toys, plus 2 double/Queen beds in the other upstairs bedrooms.

We have a bunk bed and toys, plus 2 double/Queen beds in the other upstairs bedrooms. We live in the upstairs duplex with access to the yard and a large sunny deck. We have a rental apartment on the ground floor which has a separate entrance and a
neighborhood_overview: The house is one block off Smith Street in Carroll Gardens/Gowanus with great restaurants and shops for all tastes plus access to all the subway lines heading to Manhattan and other areas of the city. There are many kid-friendly parks within walking distance, as well as easy access to the Brooklyn waterfront parks, Prospect Park, the Botanical Gardens, and the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
notes: With two children we also have plenty of kid-friendly toys and books, including a bunk bed.
transit: Many nearby subway stations provide easy access to all of Manhattan and the rest of New York City. We often walk into Manhattan over the Brooklyn Bridge. If you are driving, we park our car on surrounding neighborhood streets.
access: We live in the upstairs duplex with access to the yard and a large sunny deck. We have a rental apartment on the ground floor which has a separate entrance and a small private patio.
interaction: Because this our primary residence, we have limited availability - primarily in the summer and during school holidays - plus we love to know a bit about our our guests before confirming a reservation.
house_rules: Because this is our primary residence we ask you treat it like your home. We are non-smokers and we have no pets. We also ask that you not use our home to host events for outside guests.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: There are four of us in our family and we love living in Brooklyn. Maggie is 12 and loves reading and theater. Oliver is 9 and is obsessed with legos and all forms of building. My husband is an artist and I am a faculty member at NYU in the Art+Education program. We love to travel and often rent our house while we're away, especially in the summer. We're easy going and love to show off all the great things about our neighborhood and city. We've been renting out our house on Airbnb for many years now and enjoy meeting the people and families who stay here.

summary: PLEASE INQUIRE BEFORE BOOKING! A private "Studio Plus" apt. that's cozy and light in Brooklyn's best area. Includes utilities, cable TV, Wifi, computer, fully stocked kitchen and more.  We rent the space monthly and prefer guests to book from the 1st of the month to the end of the month (or multiple full months). However, depending on circumstances, it may be possible to check in or out in the middle of any given month. PLEASE DO NOT BOOK WITHOUT FIRST INQUIRING about details and possibilities!
space: Dear Guests, We are a Green Guest House. We cater to the chemically sensitive, allergic, and/or environmentally concerned guest. We recycle and use resources responsibly.  Our guest house is a one flight walk up. It is a private apartment in our 2-family home. The unit is not shared with any other guests. We are frequently available to answer questions, give directions/advice and even act as "concierge". The space consists of a full kitchen, bathroom with shower and claw foot bathtub, living room with pull out couch & dining table, and a separate sleeping alcove. For longer term stays it is best for 2 people, but can accommodate a child and other adults on a short term basis.  We are located in the very popular Brooklyn neighborhood of Park Slope, which has been touted as one of the 10 best neighborhoods the the USA! There are countless restaurants, cafes, clubs, museums, and the famous Prospect Park. Enjoy the amazing Brooklyn Botanic Garden, Brooklyn Museum, Prospect Park Zoo, Brookl

neighborhood_overview: Park Slope is an extremely beautiful, safe, and family-friendly neighborhood. There is lots to do and see.
notes: We are as flexible as possible with arrival and departure times. Depending on the situation, late night arrivals are fine. After check-out guests are also able to store luggage with us during the day if they have late night airport departures.
transit: We are located only two and a half blocks from 3 major subway lines, the "F", "R", and "G". There are also buses just half a block away.
access: Guests are welcome to have friends visit, but ANY EXTRA people staying overnight is an extra fee and must be cleared ahead of time. Large and/or loud parties are strictly forbidden as this is our home where children are living and where we respect our neighbors.
interaction: We greet our guests in person and usually see them on their way in and out. We are available most of the time for questions and assistance. If we have to be away for any length of time, our guests are made aware of that much ahead of time.
house_rules: Pricing is increased after 2 adults but is negotiable for stays a week or more. Children 12 and under are free. We try to keep our rate affordable by not charging a cleaning fee. Due to this we ask that all guests wash their own dishes and do their best to treat the apartment as they would their own home. There is absolutely no smoking, no loud parties, and no pets allowed.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: I live in Brooklyn, NY. I am a fellow Airbnb host, but also work as a forensic social worker in NYC. I have a husband and young child and we love hosting guests and we love Airbnb. We are serious environmentalists, which is why we opened a "green" guest house. We are active members of the Green Party in NY as well.

name: 2 BR / 2 Bath Duplex Apt with patio! East Village
summary: ***PLEASE DO NOT MAKE RESERVATION REQUEST UNTIL I CONFIRM AVAILABILITY!!!!*** NO CHECK-IN on weekends  (Sat or Sun) during the Summer (May-Sep). Please read details below in the description  for information on my apartment and what is included BEFORE you make a Reservation Request!

Included: Full use of a private apartment (no other guests) use of my 2 Bedroom, 2 full bath Duplex Apt with private outdoor patios and roof deck (shared with all tenants in building).
